[
    {
        "content": "<p>Does someone know a reference for this?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Given two commutative monoids <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M,N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> the set of monoid homomorphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{hom}(M,N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> becomes a commutative monoid with pointwise addition, and there's also a tensor product of commutative monoids with a natural isomorphism</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>N</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>N</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{hom}(M\\otimes N,L)\\cong\\text{hom}(M,\\text{hom}(N,L)).</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I am <em>not</em> primarily wanting a way to deduce this from more general facts, nor do I want to be told that it's easy to check (which is true).  I just want to use it and refer to a proof.    </p>\n<p>If I needed it only for abelian groups I'd know plenty of textbooks to cite - though it's so well-known I probably wouldn't bother.   But for some reason I don't know analogous books or papers for commutative monoids.</p>\n<p>John Berman stated it without proof <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/278429/derived-tensor-products-and-tor-of-commutative-monoids\">on MathOverflow</a>, but that doesn't help me.</p>",
        "id": 517785767,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747130177
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I haven't seen a reference for commutative monoids specifically, but it's a general fact about commutative/monoidal algebraic theories/monads ...</p>",
        "id": 517800814,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1747134883
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it would be appropriate to cite Kock's paper \"Closed categories generated by commutative monads\" together with a reference that the free commutative monoid monad is commutative, e.g. Meseguer--Montanari's \"Petri nets are monoids\".</p>",
        "id": 517806235,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1747136543
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, thanks.  I was hoping someone had written a nice book or paper on commutative monoids that covers a lot of material we often see presented for abelian groups.   (Or a book on modules of rigs that covers a lot of material we often see presented for modules of rings!)   Someday such books will exist, but maybe not yet.</p>",
        "id": 517876208,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747153967
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, I'll point readers to the more general results on commutative monads.</p>",
        "id": 517877462,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747154345
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see Montanari and Meseguer write</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It is <em>well known</em> [emphasis mine] that a tensor product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\otimes B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> can be defined in the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{CMon}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">CMon</span></span></span></span></span> of commutative monoids so that, up to natural isomorphisms, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\otimes</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊗</span></span></span></span> is associative, commutative, and has as an identity. It is also <em>well known</em> that the monoid homomorphisms from A to B form a commutative monoid [A, B] and that there is a natural isomorphism</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathsf{CMon}(A \\otimes B, C) \\cong \\mathsf{CMon}(A, [B ,C]) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">CMon</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">CMon</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">])</span></span></span></span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>in other words, the category of commutative monoids is a symmetric<br>\nmonoidal closed category (MacLane, 1971). This is just like a Cartesian<br>\nclosed category except that....</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 517879236,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747154866
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Authors using \"well known\" without providing a reference is a pet peeve of mine <span aria-label=\"slight smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"slight smile\">:slight_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 517885900,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1747156981
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is well known that a monad is a monoid in the category of endofunctors.</p>",
        "id": 517908059,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1747164734
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/tensor-hom.20duality.20for.20commutative.20monoids/near/517885900\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Authors using \"well known\" without providing a reference is a pet peeve of mine <span aria-label=\"slight smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"slight smile\">:slight_smile:</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Even worse is what I'll be doing by citing Meseguer and Montanari: saying that something is well known, and providing a reference.... to someone else who says it's well known!  But Kock's paper provides proofs, I believe (at a higher level of generality).</p>",
        "id": 517916713,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747167817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, Meseguer and Montanari at least explain why the commutative monoid monad is commutative, from which the facts you want follows from Kock's paper. So citing both references ought to cover all the bases.</p>",
        "id": 517983915,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1747205690
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The nLab page <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/tensor%20product%20of%20commutative%20monoids\">[[tensor product of commutative monoids]]</a> at least contains a construction of the tensor product, although not the internal-hom and their adjunction.  Maybe someone can add that, and then it can be a reference.  (-:</p>",
        "id": 517985858,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1747206392
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm planning to cite M&amp;M and Kock, and say as little as possible about the details.  I'm thinking of running an undergraduate project where the students prove basic theorems like this about commutative monoids and write a nice little paper about them.   (Teaching students to write would be the tiresome part.)</p>\n<p>P. A. Grillet's book <em>Commutative Semigroups</em> mentions a couple papers about tensor products of commutative semigroups, but doesn't develop them.   </p>\n<p>(I'm not sure exactly what happens when you write a large book of theorems about commutative semigroups instead of commutative monoids.)</p>",
        "id": 518007345,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747212831
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/tensor-hom.20duality.20for.20commutative.20monoids/near/517785767\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Does someone know a reference for this?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Given two commutative monoids <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M,N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> the set of monoid homomorphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{hom}(M,N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> becomes a commutative monoid with pointwise addition, and there's also a tensor product of commutative monoids with a natural isomorphism</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>N</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>hom</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>N</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{hom}(M\\otimes N,L)\\cong\\text{hom}(M,\\text{hom}(N,L)).</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I am <em>not</em> primarily wanting a way to deduce this from more general facts, nor do I want to be told that it's easy to check (which is true).  I just want to use it and refer to a proof.    </p>\n<p>If I needed it only for abelian groups I'd know plenty of textbooks to cite - though it's so well-known I probably wouldn't bother.   But for some reason I don't know analogous books or papers for commutative monoids.</p>\n<p>John Berman stated it without proof <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/278429/derived-tensor-products-and-tor-of-commutative-monoids\">on MathOverflow</a>, but that doesn't help me.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This may be an unpopular opinion, but this is a case where I would not blush to say \"it is well-known that\". Perhaps with a parenthetical \"the proof of this is just like the proof for abelian groups\". </p>\n<p>But in response to Mike's suggestion, which gives another option, I've now added the stuff about the internal homs and the adjunction to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/tensor%20product%20of%20commutative%20monoids\">[[tensor product of commutative monoids]]</a>. To me, this is the whole point of tensor products in the first place: internal homs <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[B, C]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> are defined pointwise by commutativity in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, and then the endofunctors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[B, -]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> are closed under composition, up to isomorphism, by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>∘</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>≅</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[A, -] \\circ [B, -] \\cong [A \\otimes B, -]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 519375517,
